00:52:35.750 --> 00:52:40.450
can take it out, but especially in a sunset
scene like this, the light, the light is so

00:52:40.450 --> 00:52:48.710
graduated there, it would be very hard to
take it out. Tip is, remove all filters. However,

00:52:48.710 --> 00:52:56.810
if you leave a filter on, you may get a nice
shot like this where you can see some of the

00:52:56.810 --> 00:53:01.850
effect of the filter. Ok, we're gonna wind
up here. I think, Cliff, we have five minutes

00:53:01.850 --> 00:53:02.850
left, 10?

00:53:02.850 --> 00:53:06.280
Seven minutes. I'll bet it's-- seven minutes.
My, they're really strict about time around

00:53:06.280 --> 00:53:09.010
here. Ok, I'll speed it up. I'll talk really
fast. No. I am from New York; I know I talk

00:53:09.010 --> 00:53:13.100
fast, but I'll just give you a few more tips
on wildlife photography. I was teaching a

00:53:13.100 --> 00:53:18.480
workshop over in Botswana. This is one of
my favorite pictures. It illustrates a lot

00:53:18.480 --> 00:53:23.500
of the tips that I've been talking about today.
Name of the game is to fill the frame, expose

00:53:23.500 --> 00:53:25.250
for the highlights, we don't want the highlights
overexposed and washed out. We have nice catch

00:53:25.250 --> 00:53:31.700
light in the subject's eyes. We have a little
bit of an expression. You see this animal's

00:53:31.700 --> 00:53:38.550
looking; something's going on. So, I like
that shot. That shot was like this shot, ok?

00:53:38.550 --> 00:53:43.810
The light wasn't that great. I turned this
snapshot into a much more dramatic shot simply

00:53:43.810 --> 00:53:48.160
by cropping in, using a technique that the
Renaissance painters used, that is, to darken

00:53:48.160 --> 00:53:55.619
the edges of the scene to draw more attention
to the main subject and I selectively sharpened

00:53:55.619 --> 00:54:01.020
the animal. My number one tip in the digital
darkroom is to think selectively, don't think

00:54:01.020 --> 00:54:09.260
globally. In other words, apply sharpening,
apply contrast, apply curves and levels selectively,

00:54:09.260 --> 00:54:14.730
not globally. So, I might even have, actually,
I did sharpen his face more than his body

00:54:14.730 --> 00:54:21.720
and I softened the background. Think selectively.
You could turn a snapshot into a great shot.

00:54:21.720 --> 00:54:28.130
This may look like a pretty boring picture
of some logs here and some trees, but it's

00:54:28.130 --> 00:54:33.780
actually a very interesting picture. We were
driving around and the guide says, "Look!

00:54:33.780 --> 00:54:39.720
There's a lion." So, we're like 300 yards
away, there's a lion right in here. I couldn't

00:54:39.720 --> 00:54:46.320
even see him. I had to get out my super telephoto
lens to be able to see him. When you're travelling,

00:54:46.320 --> 00:54:51.340
work with a good guide. Having a good guide
is one of the most important things. He or

00:54:51.340 --> 00:54:59.700
she will help you get the shots. So, this
is the last day of the trip. We were shooting.

00:54:59.700 --> 00:55:03.650
We were having like a great time. So we came,
we, we go into three or four different camps

00:55:03.650 --> 00:55:08.240
in the Okavango Delta. So, we're flying around
and we land on the ground. Well, we didn't

00:55:08.240 --> 00:55:12.920
land in the water on the Okavango Delta. We
land on the runway, they're shooing the elephants

00:55:12.920 --> 00:55:18.190
away and the guide comes up, he rips open
the door, he says, "Come on guys, come on.

00:55:18.190 --> 00:55:22.369
