01:00:17.619 --> 01:00:19.920
get your take on that.

01:00:19.920 --> 01:00:25.220
&gt;&gt;Rick: Well, in HDR photography, there's
basically, there's two basic styles. The realistic

01:00:25.220 --> 01:00:31.010
and the surrealistic. My friend, Trey Ratcliff,
who has spoken here, he's into both types.

01:00:31.010 --> 01:00:36.869
I've seen some of his pictures that look real
and some that look surreal. And, once again,

01:00:36.869 --> 01:00:43.880
it's up to the subject. The subject really,
I think, suggests whether or not it should

01:00:43.880 --> 01:00:49.880
be realistic or artistic. Here's an inside
of a car. This, out in Los Osos, California,

01:00:49.880 --> 01:00:52.360
this I thought looked good as a realistic
image cause I didn't want to increase the

01:00:52.360 --> 01:00:59.340
saturation, the contrast and the color. But
in another picture that I have over here,

01:00:59.340 --> 01:01:06.680
if I go down, it looks a little more-- well,
here's a--, actually, here's a realistic and

01:01:06.680 --> 01:01:13.050
here's a surrealistic. So, it's really up
to you. When HDR came out, most people were

01:01:13.050 --> 01:01:16.240
going for the surrealistic with the halos
and all those other things, but again, it's

01:01:16.240 --> 01:01:25.619
the subject. And just one tip I can give you
on HDR photography, it doesn't always, the

01:01:25.619 --> 01:01:29.940
bracketing sequence is not always-- and I'm
gonna find the slide that illustrates it--

01:01:29.940 --> 01:01:37.160
it's not always zero, two over and two under.
So, here you see I'm in the Havana Florida

01:01:37.160 --> 01:01:44.430
Hotel in Old Havana; the zero exposure compensation
setting is on the left. I only had to go two

01:01:44.430 --> 01:01:50.220
stops over to see into the shadows, but because
I didn't want the highlights blown out, I

01:01:50.220 --> 01:01:55.750
had to go two stops under, three stops under,
four stops under. Now, in this picture of

01:01:55.750 --> 01:02:02.440
the red car, it was exactly the opposite because
I wanted to see into the shadows. So, here's

01:02:02.440 --> 01:02:08.530
the average exposure at zero on the top left,
and I only had to go two stops under so I

01:02:08.530 --> 01:02:11.380
preserve the highlights out the window, but
then two stops over, three stops over, four

01:02:11.380 --> 01:02:17.530
stops over, five stops over. The idea is you're
not always zero and you're not always two

01:02:17.530 --> 01:02:20.859
over and two under. Yes.

